article.description: The Sacramento Kings, who had the NBA's best home record last season, took a step toward respectability on the road this year.
article.headline: Kings hold off Clips for third road win
article.linkText: Kings perfect at home 3-7 on road after beating Clips
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Sacramento Kings, who had the NBA's best home record last season, took a step toward respectability on the road this year. "On the road, you have to be consistent and we haven't been consistent enough,'' Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said after Wednesday night's 93-89 win over the Los Angeles Clippers. "We just have to work harder.'' The victory was only the Kings' third in seven road games. Chris Webber and Bobby Jackson each scored 19 points, Peja Stojakovic added 16 and reserve Hedo Turkoglu had 11 for the Kings. "We did a decent job in the second half with the big guys getting some touches,'' Adelman said. Corey Maggette scored a career-high 30 points for the Clippers, including a 3-pointer with 21.7 seconds left that pulled them within two at 91-89. But Stojakovic made two free throws, then the Clippers missed three shots in a row their final time down the court -- a 3-point try by Eric Piatkowski and two jumpers in the lane by Michael Olowokandi. Elton Brand had 21 points and 10 rebounds for the Clippers, with Webber holding him to six points and one rebound after halftime. "I was in foul trouble in the second half and I guess that was a blessing in disguise because I just wanted to keep the ball out of Brand's hands by fronting him,'' said Webber, who had four fouls in the first half and none in the second. "Elton is a great player. He has taken rebounding to another level and he is very unselfish.'' The Clippers, 1-6 at home, were up 68-63 heading into the final quarter, but blew the lead for the fourth time this season when leading after three quarters. "We controlled the game, but they made their run and made the big plays down the stretch. We put ourselves in a position to make something happen, but we didn't do it,'' said the Clippers' Andre Miller, who had 11 points and seven assists -- but also made six turnovers. Trailing by five, the Kings began the fourth with a 10-2 run over the opening four minutes. Turkoglu, Webber and Doug Christie made consecutive 20-footers to key the spurt, which put Sacramento up 73-70. The Kings never trailed afterward. Christie added a 3-pointer for an 87-80 lead with 3:15 remaining, and the Kings held on from there to win for only the fifth time in their last 15 games against the Clippers in Los Angeles. A spurt of good defense -- including two blocks apiece by Olowokandi and Brand -- and fastbreaks brought the crowd of 18,087 to its feet and gave the Clippers a 68-62 lead late in the third quarter. Webber and Christie each had two of their shots swatted during the four-minute surge as Los Angeles came back from a 60-59 deficit.

Game notes
Both the Kings and Clippers expect key players to return next month. Sacramento's Mike Bibby, who had foot surgery, is expected back around the middle of December, and the Clippers' Lamar Odom, out with ankle and wrist problems, hopes to return by Christmas. ... The Kings also were without Scot Pollard, who has a stress fracture in his lower back. ... Although the Kings have a 13-27 record against the Clippers in Los Angeles, Sacramento beat them at Staples Center for a milestone victory last April. The 125-106 win over the Clippers gave the Kings their first Pacific Division title and assured them homecourt advantage throughout the playoffs.
